{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6991fa7a-2548-4074-879b-da1c3c08dfd8","content":"Use `Assert.ThrowsException<T>` (MSTest) or `Assert.Throws<T>` (xUnit/NUnit) instead:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()\n{\n    var service = new UserService();\n\n    var ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n        () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\n\n    Assert.AreEqual(\"email\", ex.ParamName); // bonus: verify details\n}\n```\n\n**Why switch:**\n- `[ExpectedException]` passes if the exception is thrown *anywhere* in the test — even in the arrange step — masking bugs.\n- `Assert.ThrowsException` scopes the check to the exact call, and returns the exception so you can assert on its properties (message, param name, inner exception, etc.).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"adcc9354-0818-44cf-a2cf-5765e2db3d49","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about modernizing a C# test that uses the `[ExpectedException]` attribute. This is a general knowledge question - no need to explore a codebase.","outputTokens":263,"requestId":"7C17:A8FAA:27FD230:2C49695:69F946DF"},"id":"b6c3e132-a90a-4474-a551-b8b8e92bbbc9","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:24:54.027Z","parentId":"5be4fd24-dab0-4d7a-88a5-0786328ec41e"}
